snippet.textDisplay: Switching to ARM based CPUs is great for battery life, although at the cost of performance. So why are Apple making their desktops run on ARM chips? After having to repurchase all of my software for the switch from PowerPC chips in 2006, then having to do it again when Apple dropped support for 32bit applications, I have to do it again to switch to ARM architecture? What part of this is good for businesses? The number one priority when designing computers for getting actual work done is compatibility, which apparently Apple doesn't give a flying f about.
